explanation:
- OS_common_record_t: Needed to see the type/qualifier of the name_entry member (e.g. char * vs const char * or char[]). The strncpy source argument comes from record->name_entry, so determining whether that member is const-qualified is central to the MISRA const-pointer check.
- OS_module_internal_record_t: Needed to see the type/qualifier of the file_name member (e.g. char * vs const char * or char[]). module->file_name is used as the strncpy source, so its constness must be known.
- OS_module_prop_t: Needed to see the declarations/qualifiers of the name and filename members (arrays or pointers, and whether they are const). This tells whether these buffers legitimately must be writable (so non-const is required) or could be const.
- OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET (macro): This macro yields the record/module pointer from the table and token. Its expansion may introduce casts or qualifiers (const or non-const) that affect whether the returned pointer should be treated const-qualified.
- OS_global_module_table and OS_module_table: Their declarations/types (and any const qualification) determine whether the entries they contain are const-qualified; this impacts whether OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET can/should return pointers-to-const.
- OS_ModuleGetInfo_Impl (prototype): The signature (especially the second parameter type) shows whether module_prop is intended to be modified by the implementation (non-const) or only read (could be const). That affects whether module_prop should be const-qualified when possible.
- OS_ObjectIdGetById (prototype): Its contract/return semantics determine whether the token returned grants read-only access or mutable access to the object tables; this can affect whether the pointers obtained from OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET should be treated as const.
- OS_ObjectIdRelease (prototype): Included to confirm lifecycle/ownership semantics of the token and whether the object access obtained between GetById and Release is intended to be read-only versus writable (affects const qualification decisions).
- OS_CHECK_POINTER (macro): May involve casts, annotations or behavior that affect pointer constness checking (e.g. if it enforces writeability or documents intended use). Knowing its definition helps ensure the input pointer module_prop is correctly classified.

These symbols provide the type and qualifier information (and the access/ownership semantics) required to decide if any of the pointers used in OS_ModuleInfo could and should be declared to point to const-qualified types under MISRA guidance.
